<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How does force carbonation work?", answer: "Force carbonation pushes CO2 from a tank into a sealed keg of beer at a specific pressure. The CO2 dissolves into the beer until the dissolved CO2 reaches equilibrium with the headspace pressure. By controlling the temperature and pressure you control the dissolved CO2, and by waiting one to two weeks at the equilibrium pressure you produce stable, predictable carbonation." },
  { question: "Why does temperature matter so much?", answer: "Cold beer dissolves more CO2 than warm beer. At 38 degrees Fahrenheit you only need about 11 PSI to reach 2.5 volumes, but at 60 degrees you would need around 22 PSI for the same carbonation. Always force carbonate in the kegerator at serving temperature so the same pressure that carbonates the beer also serves it without foaming or losing carbonation." },
  { question: "What pressure should I use?", answer: "Set the regulator to the equilibrium PSI for your target CO2 volumes at your serving temperature. For most American craft beer at 38 degrees, that means 10 to 13 PSI. For low-carbed British ales it might be 5 to 8 PSI. For highly sparkling Belgian ales or wheats you need 14 to 18 PSI. The calculator returns the exact pressure for your inputs." },
  { question: "How long does force carbonation take?", answer: "Set and forget at serving pressure takes 7 to 14 days to fully equilibrate, but the beer is drinkable after 5 days. The shake-and-rock method speeds it up to 24 to 48 hours but is harder to dial in precisely. The calculator assumes set-and-forget at the displayed pressure." },
  { question: "What is the highest carbonation a keg can hold?", answer: "Standard Cornelius and Sankey kegs are rated to 130 PSI and routinely operate at 30 PSI without any issue. Practical force carbonation maxes out around 30 PSI, which corresponds to roughly 4.0 volumes at typical serving temperatures. Beyond that you would need higher pressure than serving systems can handle without long beer lines and nucleation control." }
]) %>

